04378nam a22006975i 9780857458964DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2012032448  a97808574589647 a10.1515/97808574589642doi  a(DE-B1597)637148  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHQ1868b.A44 2013 4aHQ1868b.A44 2013 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a305.40996122231 aAddo, Ping-Ann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCreating a Nation with Cloth :bWomen, Wealth, and Tradition in the Tongan Diaspora /cPing-Ann Addo. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aASAO Studies in Pacific Anthropology ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Nation, Cloth, and Diaspora: Locating Langa Fonua -- tChapter 1. Migration, Tradition, and Barkcloth: Authentic Innovations in Textile Gift -- tChapter 2. Gender, Materiality, and Value: Tongan Women’s Cooperatives in New Zealand -- tChapter 3. Women, Roots, and Routes: Life Histories and Life Paths -- tChapter 4. Gender, Kinship, and Economics: Transacting in Prestige and Complex Ceremonial Gift -- tChapter 5. Cash, Death, and Diaspora: When Koloa Won’t Do -- tChapter 6. Church, Cash, and Competition: Multi-Centrism and Modern Religion -- tConclusion. Moving, Dwelling, and Transforming Spaces -- tGlossary of Polynesian Terms -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTongan women living outside of their island homeland create and use hand-made, sometimes hybridized, textiles to maintain and rework their cultural traditions in diaspora. Central to these traditions is an ancient concept of homeland or nation— fonua—which Tongans retain as an anchor for modern nation-building. Utilizing the concept of the “multi-territorial nation,” the author questions the notion that living in diaspora is mutually exclusive with authentic cultural production and identity. The globalized nation the women build through gifting their barkcloth and fine mats, challenges the normative idea that nations are always geographically bounded or spatially contiguous. The work suggests that, contrary to prevalent understandings of globalization, global resource flows do not always primarily involve commodities. Focusing on first-generation Tongans in New Zealand and the relationships they forge across generations and throughout the diaspora, the book examines how these communities centralize the diaspora by innovating and adapting traditional cultural forms in unprecedented ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aTextile fabricszTonga. 0aWomenzTongaxEconomic conditions. 0aWomenzTongaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745896440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857458964423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857458964/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK